name: Precipitation in gauge
description: Total precipitation amount in gauge (accumulated since last emptying). Timing for emptying and algoritm for calculating the precipitation amount depends on sensortype
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'precipitation_amount', 'method': 'accumulated', 'methodDescription': 'Accumulated from 0, which means the sum over an unknown period.'}
cfConvention: {'standardName': 'precipitation_amount', 'cellMethod': 'time: sum (accumulated since the value was 0)', 'unit': 'kg m-2', 'version': '44'}

name: Air pressure as measured at sensor height

calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'air_pressure'}

name: Air pressure at sea level
description: Air pressure reduced to mean sea level. The parameter is usually called QFF in aviation and shows the measured air pressure reduced to mean sea level by applying actual atmospheric conditions.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'air_pressure_at_sea_level'}

name: Air pressure (QNH)
description: Air pressure reduced to sea level by applying the ICAO Standard Atmosphere. Used in aviation and the parameter is then usually called QNH. Rounded down to the nearest hPa.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'air_pressure_at_sea_level_qnh'}

name: Air temperature

name: Air temperature -vertical diff

name: Automatic METAR

name: Wind force in Beaufort

calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'beaufort_wind_force'}

name: Homogenised maximum air temperature (24 h)

name: Homogenised mean temperature (24 h)
description: Homogenised daily mean temperature. The mean is an arithmetic mean of 24 hourly values (00-00 UTC), or a formula based mean value when only a limited number of observations is available (e.g. 06, 12, 18 UTC).
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'air_temperature', 'method': 'best_estimate_mean', 'period': 'P1D', 'methodDescription': 'Best estimimate mean values are homogenized mean values. This means a high quality dataset of mean values with no kind of breaks in the timeseries.'}

name: Fair weather (24 h)
description: Fair weather. Daily value: If the sum of cloud cover values at 06, 12 and 18 UTC is 4 or lower the day is defined as a day with fair weather, and the parameter value is set equal to 1. If the sum is higher than 4 the parameter value is set equal to 0.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'cloud_area_fraction', 'method': 'boolean_clear_sky_weather', 'period': 'P1D', 'methodDescription': 'The sum of the cloud cover observations at 06, 12 and 18 UTC. The sum should be below 4 (max 24 if all overcast), then it is clear sky weather and boolean is true, that means 1, else 0 (false).'}
cfConvention: {'standardName': 'cloud_area_fraction', 'cellMethod': 'time: sum (algorithm for occurences, boolean value 1 if found 0 if not)', 'unit': '1', 'version': '44'}

name: Mostly fair weather (24 h)
description: Mostly fair weather. Daily value: If the sum of cloud cover values at 06, 12 and 18 UTC is between 5 and 9 the day is defined as a day with mostly fair weather, and the parameter value is set equal to 1. If the sum is lower than 5 or higher than 9 the parameter value is set equal to 0.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'cloud_area_fraction', 'method': 'boolean_fair_weather', 'period': 'P1D', 'methodDescription': 'The sum of the cloud cover observations at 06 and 12 UTC where no single values above 4, (and at 18 utc is 9 or lower?). The sum should be below 9 (max 24 if all overcast), then it is fair weather and boolean is true, that means 1, else 0 (false).'}
cfConvention: {'standardName': 'cloud_area_fraction', 'cellMethod': 'time: sum (algorithm for occurences, boolean value 1 if found 0 if not)', 'unit': '1', 'version': '44'}

name: Overcast weather (24 h)
description: Overcast weather. Daily value: If the sum of cloud cover values at 06, 12 and 18 UTC is 20 or higher the day is defined as a day with overcast weather, and the parameter value is set equal to 1. If the sum is lower than 20 the parameter value is set equal to 0.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'cloud_area_fraction', 'method': 'boolean_overcast_weather', 'period': 'P1D', 'methodDescription': 'The sum of the cloud cover observations at 06, 12 and 18 UTC. The sum should be 20 or more (max 24 if all overcast), then it is overcast weather and boolean is true, that means 1, else 0 (false).'}

name: METAR code CAVOK
description: Boolean parameter indicating if the code word CAVOK was present in the METAR (aviation weather report). Code word CAVOK replaces the visibility, present weather and cloud groups when the following conditions are simultaneously met: – Visibility is 10 km or more; – There is no cloud below 1 500 m (5 000 ft) or below the highest minimum sector altitude, whichever is greater, and no cumulonimbus; – There is no significant weather phenomenon as contained in Code table 4678 the Manual on Codes (WMO-No. 306), Volume I.1, Part A – Alphanumeric codes, section C.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'ceiling_and_visibility_ok'}

name: Cloud cover
description: Total cloud cover is registered using a code 0 - 8 describing how many eights of the sky are covered by clouds (0 = no clouds, 8 = completely overcast. Code -3 or 9 = cloud cover can not be estimated because the sky is obstructed from view because of fog, drifting snow etc. Code -3 is presented as ".").
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'cloud_area_fraction'}

name: Cloud cover (lowest level, METAR)
description: Cloud cover (in octas) at height HS1 (metar code FEW, SCT, BKN or OVC converted to octas (2,4,6,8)) Cloud cover not known, code=-3, presented as '.'
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'cloud_area_fraction1'}

name: Cloud cover (level 2, METAR)
description: Cloud cover (in octas) at height HS2 (metar code FEW, SCT, BKN or OVC converted to octas (2,4,6,8)) Cloud cover not known, code=-3, presented as '.'
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'cloud_area_fraction2'}

name: Cloud cover (level 3, METAR)
description: Cloud cover (in octas) at height HS3 (metar code FEW, SCT, BKN or OVC converted to octas (2,4,6,8)) Cloud cover not known, code=-3, presented as '.'
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'cloud_area_fraction3'}

name: Cloud cover (level 4, METAR)
description: Cloud cover (in octas) at height HS4 (metar code FEW, SCT, BKN or OVC converted to octas (2,4,6,8)). Cloud cover not known, code=-3, presented as '.'
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'cloud_area_fraction4'}

name: Cloud base height
description: Height of lowest cloud base, reported with code, converted to meters. Code -3 = cloud cover can not be estimated due to fog, drifting snow etc. Code -3 is presented as '.'  (in synop code=9))
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'cloud_base_height'}

name: Cloud base height (lowest level)
description: Height of cloud base 1 (clouds in group cloud_area_fraction1)
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'cloud_base_height1'}

name: Cloud base height (level 2)
description: Height of cloud base 2 (clouds in group cloud_area_fraction2)
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'cloud_base_height2'}

name: Cloud base height (level 3)
description: Height of cloud base 3 (clouds in group cloud_area_fraction3)
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'cloud_base_height3'}

name: Cloud base height (level 4)
description: Height of cloud base 4 (clouds in group cloud_area_fraction4)
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'cloud_base_height4'}

name: Cloud base height (level 1)
description: Height of cloud top of cloud base 1 (clouds in group cloud_area_fraction1)
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'cloud_top_height1'}

name: Cloud base height (level 2)
description: Height of cloud top of cloud base 2 (clouds in group cloud_area_fraction2)
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'cloud_top_height2'}

name: Cloud base height (level 3)
description: Height of cloud top of cloud base 3 (clouds in group cloud_area_fraction3)
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'cloud_top_height3'}

name: Cloud base height (level 4)
description: Height of cloud top of cloud base 4 (clouds in group cloud_area_fraction4)
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'cloud_top_height4'}

name: Genus of cloud, lowest cloud layer
description: Cloud type or genus of cloud for the lowest cloud layer, genus from WMO code table 0500. 1 refers to the layer with height cloud_base_height1 (HS1). Additional information for cloud_area_fraction1 (NS1)
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'cloud_type1'}

name: Genus of cloud, second cloud layer
description: Cloud type or genus of cloud for the lowest cloud layer, genus from WMO code table 0500. 2 refers to the layer with height cloud_base_height2 (HS2). Additional information for cloud_area_fraction2 (NS2)
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'cloud_type2'}

name: Genus of cloud, third cloud layer

calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'cloud_type3'}

name: Genus of cloud, forth cloud layer

calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'cloud_type4'}

name: Significant cloud type 1, METAR
description: Additional cloud information for group HS1/NS1, tells if CB (cumulonimbus) or TCU (towering cumulus) are present. 1 refers to cloud_base_height1.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'cloud_type_icao1'}

name: Significant cloud type 2, METAR

calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'cloud_type_icao2'}

name: Significant cloud type 3, METAR
description: Additional cloud information for group HS3/NS3, tells if CB (cumulonimbus) or TCU (towering cumulus) are present. 3 refers to cloud_base_height3.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'cloud_type_icao3'}

name: Significant cloud type 4, METAR

name: True bearing of principal ice edge

calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'direction_of_sea_ice_edge'}

Values from 1 to 8, where 1 is the sector towards northeast, 2 toward east, 3 toward southeast, 4 toward south, 5 toward southwest, 6 toward west, 7 toward northwest and 8 toward north.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'direction_of_visibility_in_air_operationally_significant'}

This elementID is connected to visibility_in_predominant. Values from 1 to 8, where 1 is the sector towards northeast, 2 toward east, 3 toward southeast, 4 toward south, 5 toward southwest, 6 toward west, 7 toward northwest and 8 toward north.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'direction_of_visibility_in_air_predominant'}

name: Flourescence from clorophyl in sea water
description: Flourescence from chlorophyl in sea water. Flourescence is re-emmitance of electromagnetic radiation that a material has absorbed. Generally, sunlight will be absorbed, and more long waved radiation will be re-emmitted. Both water-microscopic algae and colored dissoved organic matter in sea water have flourescence properties, and my measuring the flourecence the amount of these in the sea water can be estimated.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'flourescence_of_chlorophyl_a_in_sea_water'}

name: Flourescence from dissolved organic carbon in sea water

Generally, sunlight will be absorbed, and more long waved radiation will be re-emmitted. Both water-microscopic algae and colored dissoved organic matter in sea water have flourescence properties, and my measuring the flourecence the amount of these in the sea water can be estimated.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'flourescense_of_dissolved_organic_carbon_in_sea_water'}

name: Flow rate at inlet

name: Fresh water temperature

calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'fresh_water_temperature'}

name: Grass temperature

calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'grass_temperature'}

name: Indicator for type of station and type of weather information (SYNOP)

Also includes information about whether present and past weather data is included in the message and which codetables have been used for past and present weather. Uses the WMO code table 1860
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'indicator_station_type_weather'}

name: Heating degree days, 17 ºC (24 h)
description: Daily sum of heating degree days. A heating degree day (HDD) is a proxy for the energy demand needed for indoor heating. HDD is defined as how many degrees below 17 ºC the hourly mean temperature is. If the hourly mean temperature is 17 ºC or above, the  HDD is defined as zero.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'air_temperature', 'method': 'integral_of_deficit', 'innerMethod': 'mean', 'period': 'P1D', 'innerPeriod': 'P1D', 'addition': '17.0', 'methodDescription': 'Accumulated deviation below a threshold over time. Temperature deficit is defined as the sum over days, of temperature threshold minus the daily mean air temperatures, taking only into account the temperatures below the threshold. This metric is often named after a specification and "degree-days", e.g. heating degree-days.', 'innerMethodDescription': 'Standard arithmetic mean value for the given period'}

name: Heating degree days, 17 ºC (month)
description: Monthly sum of heating degree days. A heating degree day (HDD) is a proxy for the energy demand needed for indoor heating. HDD is defined as how many degrees below 17 ºC the daily mean temperature is. If the daily mean temperature is 17 ºC or above, the  HDD is defined as zero.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'air_temperature', 'method': 'integral_of_deficit', 'innerMethod': 'mean', 'period': 'P1M', 'innerPeriod': 'P1D', 'addition': '17.0', 'methodDescription': 'Accumulated deviation below a threshold over time. Temperature deficit is defined as the sum over days, of temperature threshold minus the daily mean air temperatures, taking only into account the temperatures below the threshold. This metric is often named after a specification and "degree-days", e.g. heating degree-days.', 'innerMethodDescription': 'Standard arithmetic mean value for the given period'}

name: Heating degree days, 17 ºC (year)
description: Annual sum of heating degree days. A heating degree day (HDD) is a proxy for the energy demand needed for indoor heating. HDD is defined as how many degrees below 17 ºC the daily mean temperature is. If the daily mean temperature is 17 ºC or above, the  HDD is defined as zero.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'air_temperature', 'method': 'integral_of_deficit', 'innerMethod': 'mean', 'period': 'P1Y', 'innerPeriod': 'P1D', 'addition': '17.0', 'methodDescription': 'Accumulated deviation below a threshold over time. Temperature deficit is defined as the sum over days, of temperature threshold minus the daily mean air temperatures, taking only into account the temperatures below the threshold. This metric is often named after a specification and "degree-days", e.g. heating degree-days.', 'innerMethodDescription': 'Standard arithmetic mean value for the given period'}

name: Heating degree days, 17 ºC (season)
description: Seasonal sum of heating degree days. Winter (Dec,Jan,Feb), spring (Mar,Apr,May), summer (Jun,Jul,Aug) and autumn (Sep,Oct,Nov). If the daily mean temperature is 17 ºC or above, the  HDD is defined as zero.

If the daily mean temperature is equal to or lower than 0 ºC the heat sum is defined as zero.

name: Cloud cover, lowest clouds
description: Amount of all low clouds (CL), or -amount of middle clouds (CM) if there are no low clouds. It is registered using a code 0 - 8 describing how many eights of the sky are covered by low clouds (0 = no clouds, 8 = completely overcast. Code -3 or 9 = cloud cover can not be estimated because the sky is obstructed from view because of fog, drifting snow etc. Code -3 is presented as ".").
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'low_type_cloud_area_fraction'}

name: Concentration of blue green algae
description: The amount of blue-green algae in a water sample given as a mass concentration. Blue-green algae, or cyanobacteria, are bateria that thrives in warm, nutrient-rich water. The bacteria produces oxygen through photosynthesis, but can also in some cases produce toxins that are hamful for humans and animals. The parameter is not measurable with sensors but calculated based on flourecence and lab samples. This can be used to create a function that can estimate the values for the next measurement period, but to get the correct result new samples must be taken.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'mass_concentration_of_blue_green_algae_in_sea_water'}

name: Concentration of chlorophyll
description: The amount of chlorophyll in a water sample given as a mass concentration. Chlorophylls are the green pigments found in most plants, algae and cyanobacteria; their presence is essential for photosynthesis to take place. The parameter is not measurable with sensors but calculated based on flourecence and lab samples. This can be used to create a function that can estimate the values for the next measurement period, but to get the correct result new samples must be taken.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'mass_concentration_of_chlorophyll_in_sea_water'}

name: Concentration of cryptophytes
description: The amount of cryptophytes in a water sample given as a mass concentration. Cryptophtes are one-celled algae, capable of performing photosyntesis. The parameter is not measurable with sensors but calculated based on flourecence and lab samples. This can be used to create a function that can estimate the values for the next measurement period, but to get the correct result new samples must be taken.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'mass_concentration_of_cryptophytes_in_sea_water'}

name: Concentration of diatoms
description: The amount of diatoms in a water sample given as a mass concentration. Diatoms are single-celled phytoplankton with an external skeleton made of silica. Phytoplankton are a algae that grow where there is sufficient light to support photosynthesis. The parameter is not measurable with sensors but calculated based on flourecence and lab samples. This can be used to create a function that can estimate the values for the next measurement period, but to get the correct result new samples must be taken.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'mass_concentration_of_diatoms_in_sea_water'}

name: Concentration of green algae

calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'sea_surface_wave_period', 'method': 'max', 'period': 'PT20M', 'methodDescription': 'Maximum value observed or calculated in the given period'}

name: Max Significant Wave Height (24 h)
description: Daily maximum of significant wave height, instrumentally measured. Significant wave height is a statistic computed from wave measurements and corresponds to the average height of the highest one third of the waves, where the height is defined as the vertical distance from a wave trough to the following wave crest.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'sea_surface_wave_significant_height', 'method': 'max', 'period': 'P1D', 'methodDescription': 'Maximum value observed or calculated in the given period'}

name: Max Significant Wave Height (month)
description: Monthly maximum of significant wave height, instrumentally measured. Significant wave height is a statistic computed from wave measurements and corresponds to the average height of the highest one third of the waves, where the height is defined as the vertical distance from a wave trough to the following wave crest.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'sea_surface_wave_significant_height', 'method': 'max', 'period': 'P1M', 'methodDescription': 'Maximum value observed or calculated in the given period'}

name: Maximum snow cover (month)
description: Largest observed snow cover value per month. Snow cover is registered using a code 0-4. 1=mostly snow free ground. 2=equal parts of snow covered and snow free ground. 3=mostly snow covered ground. 4=Completely snow covered ground. Code=0 or -1 means "no snow" (-1 is presented as ".").
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'snow_coverage_type', 'method': 'max', 'period': 'P1M', 'methodDescription': 'Maximum value observed or calculated in the given period'}

name: Maximum snow cover (season)
description: Largest observed snow cover value per season. Snow cover is registered using a code 0-4. 1=mostly snow free ground. 2=equal parts of snow covered and snow free ground. 3=mostly snow covered ground. 4=Completely snow covered ground. Code=0 or -1 means "no snow" (-1 is presented as ".").  A season covers three months: Winter (Dec,Jan,Feb), spring (Mar,Apr,May), summer (Jun,Jul,Aug) and autumn (Sep,Oct,Nov).
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'snow_coverage_type', 'method': 'max', 'period': 'P3M', 'methodDescription': 'Maximum value observed or calculated in the given period'}

name: Maximum snow temperature (1h)
description: Maximum minute value per hour. Snow temperature can be measured at different depths, but the default is 10 cm.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'snow_temperature', 'method': 'max', 'period': 'PT1H', 'methodDescription': 'Maximum value observed or calculated in the given period'}

name: Sunshine duration - most hours of sunshine per day (month)
description: Number of sunshine hours during day of month with most sunshine
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'duration_of_sunshine', 'method': 'max', 'innerMethod': 'sum', 'period': 'P1M', 'innerPeriod': 'P1D', 'methodDescription': 'Maximum value observed or calculated in the given period', 'innerMethodDescription': 'The arithmetic sum of data values or accumulated value in a given period.'}

name: Sunshine duration (season)
description: Number of sunshine hours during day of the season with most amount of sunshine. A season covers three months: Winter (Dec,Jan,Feb), spring (Mar,Apr,May), summer (Jun,Jul,Aug) and autumn (Sep,Oct,Nov).
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'duration_of_sunshine', 'method': 'max', 'innerMethod': 'sum', 'period': 'P3M', 'innerPeriod': 'P1D', 'methodDescription': 'Maximum value observed or calculated in the given period', 'innerMethodDescription': 'The arithmetic sum of data values or accumulated value in a given period.'}

name: Maximum daily precipitation sum (month)

name: Maksimum virtual temperature (1 h)
description: Highest virtual temperature per hour. The virtual temperature of air is the temperature at which the dry air constituent of a parcel of moist air would have the same density as the moist air at the same pressure. This parameter virtual temperature is calculated by taking advantage of the temperature depencence of the speed of sound.

name: Max Runway Visual Range excceeding measuring range at runwayid 1
description: One letter code that indicates if the Maximum Runway Visual Range exceeding measuring range, at runway id 1. The lower limit of the reporting range should be 50 m; below this limit, reports should merely indicate that the RVR is less than 50 m (M0050, code will be M). The upper limit of the reporting range should be 2000 m; above this limit, reports should merely indicate that the RVR is more than 2000 m (P2000, the code will be P). The runwayid can be found in the elementid runway_id1

name: Max Runway Visual Range excceeding measuring range at runwayid 2
description: One letter code that indicates if the Maximum Runway Visual Range exceeding measuring range, at runway id 2. The lower limit of the reporting range should be 50 m; below this limit, reports should merely indicate that the RVR is less than 50 m (M0050, code will be M). The upper limit of the reporting range should be 2000 m; above this limit, reports should merely indicate that the RVR is more than 2000 m (P2000, the code will be P). The runwayid can be found in the elementid runway_id2

name: Max Runway Visual Range excceeding measuring range at runwayid 3

The upper limit of the reporting range should be 2000 m; above this limit, reports should merely indicate that the RVR is more than 2000 m (P2000, the code will be P). The runwayid can be found in the elementid runway_id3

Bulk soil refers the total mass of soil, water, and air in the sample.

name: Mean relative permittivity (dielectric behavior) of bulk soil (1 h)
description: The mean value of relative permittivity (in soil) over the last hour. The relative permittivity(dielectric behavior) of a material is generally defined as the factor by which the capacitance of a plate capacitor increases when the vacuum or air between the plates is replaced by that material. The bulk soil relative permittivity is the apparent permittivity of the sampled soil-water-air volume relative to the permittivity of vaccum or air.  The bulk soil relative permittivity is defined as the factor by which the capacitance of a plate capacitor increases when the vacuum or air between the plates is replace by the sampled material, here the sampled soil-water-air bulk

name: Mean directional spread
description: Defined by Goda et al. (1981) and calculated using the first and second-order Fourier coefficients. Directional spread is the (one-sided) directional width within a given sub-domain of the wave directional spectrum, S(t,x,y,f,theta) where t is time, x and y are horizontal coordinates (such as longitude and latitude), f is frequency and theta is direction. For a given mean wave (beam) direction the quantity approximates half the root mean square width about the beam axis, as derived either directly from circular moments or via the Fourier components of the wave directional spectrum.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'sea_surface_wave_directional_spread', 'method': 'mean', 'methodDescription': 'Standard arithmetic mean value for the given period'}

name: Mean wave height - swell1
description: Mean height of the main swell wave system. Swell waves are waves on the ocean surface and are the low frequency portion of a bimodal wave frequency spectrum. The wave height is defined as the vertical distance from a wave trough to the following wave crest.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'sea_surface_swell_wave_first_mean_height'}

name: Mean wave period - swell 1
description: Mean wave period of the main swell wave system. Swell waves are waves on the ocean surface and are the low frequency portion of a bimodal wave frequency spectrum. A period is an interval of time, or the time-period of an oscillation. Wave period is the interval of time between repeated features on the waveform such as crests, troughs or upward passes through the mean level. Wave mean period is the mean period measured over the observation duration.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'sea_surface_swell_wave_first_mean_period'}

name: Swell wave direction
description: Swell waves are waves on the ocean surface and are the low frequency portion of a bimodal wave frequency spectrum. The phrase "from_direction" is used in the construction X_from_direction and indicates the direction from which the velocity vector of X is coming. The direction is a bearing in the usual geographical sense, measured positive clockwise from due north.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'sea_surface_swell_wave_from_direction'}

name: Direction of swell system 1
description: Direction of swell system (HW1)
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'sea_surface_swell_wave_from_direction_of_first_mean_height'}

name: Direction of swell system 2
description: Direction of the secondary swell system. Swell waves are waves on the ocean surface and are the low frequency portion of a bimodal wave frequency spectrum. The mean wave height of this system is described by sea_surface_swell_wave_second_mean_height
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'sea_surface_swell_wave_from_direction_of_second_mean_height'}

name: Mean swell wave direction
description: Mean direction for swell waves. Swell waves are waves on the ocean surface and are the low frequency portion of a bimodal wave frequency spectrum. The division between high and low frequencies are sensor specific, check metadata for details.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'sea_surface_swell_wave_from_mean_direction_of_total_energy'}

name: Wave period of swell waves
description: The swell wave directional spectrum can be written as a five dimensional function S(t,x,y,f,theta) where t is time, x and y are horizontal coordinates (such as longitude and latitude), f is frequency and theta is direction. S can be integrated over direction to give S1= integral(S dtheta). Frequency moments, M(n) of S1 can then be calculated as follows: M(n) = integral(S1 f^n df), where f^n is f to the power of n. The second wave period, T(m2), is calculated as the square root of the ratio M(0)/M(2).
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'sea_surface_swell_wave_mean_period_from_variance_spectral_density_second_frequency_moment'}

name: Mean wave height - swell 2
description: Mean height of the secondary swell wave system. Swell waves are waves on the ocean surface and are the low frequency portion of a bimodal wave frequency spectrum. The wave height is defined as the vertical distance from a wave trough to the following wave crest.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'sea_surface_swell_wave_second_mean_height'}

name: Mean wave period - swell2
description: Mean wave period of the secondary swell wave system. Swell waves are waves on the ocean surface and are the low frequency portion of a bimodal wave frequency spectrum. A period is an interval of time, or the time-period of an oscillation. Wave period is the interval of time between repeated features on the waveform such as crests, troughs or upward passes through the mean level. Wave mean period is the mean period measured over the observation duration.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'sea_surface_swell_wave_second_mean_period'}

name: Significant height of swell waves
description: Swell waves are waves on the ocean surface and are the low frequency portion of a bimodal wave frequency spectrum. Significant wave height is a statistic computed from wave measurements and corresponds to the average height of the highest one third of the waves, where the height is defined as the vertical distance from a wave trough to the following wave crest.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'sea_surface_swell_wave_significant_height'}

name: Sea surface temperature
description: Sea temperature near the water surface
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'sea_surface_temperature'}

name: Wave directional spread
description: Directional spread is the (one-sided) directional width within a given sub-domain of the wave directional spectrum, S(t,x,y,f,theta) where t is time, x and y are horizontal coordinates (such as longitude and latitude), f is frequency and theta is direction. For a given mean wave (beam) direction the quantity approximates half the root mean square width about the beam axis, as derived either directly from circular moments or via the Fourier components of the wave directional spectrum.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'sea_surface_wave_directional_spread'}

name: Directional width

name: Long Crestedness parameter

name: Mean wave direction

name: Mean wave direction of the most energetic waves

name: Height of steepest wave
description: Height of the steepest wave measured during the observation period. Wave steepness is defined as the ratio of the wave height divided by the wavelength. Wave height is defined as the vertical distance from a wave trough to the following wave crest. The wavelength is the horizontal distance between repeated features on the waveform such as crests, troughs or upward passes through the mean level.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'sea_surface_wave_height_of_steepest_wave'}

name: Wave Height, highest wave
description: Height of the highest individual wave in meters. Wave height is defined as the vertical distance from a wave trough to the following wave crest. The maximum wave height is the greatest trough to crest distance measured during the observation period.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'sea_surface_wave_maximum_height'}

name: Maximum Wave Period
description: The maximum wave period is the longest wave period measured during the observation period. A period is an interval of time, or the time-period of an oscillation. Wave period is the interval of time between repeated features on the waveform such as crests, troughs or upward passes through the mean level.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'sea_surface_wave_maximum_period'}

name: Maximum wave steepness
description: Maximum wave steepness is the maximum value measured during the observation period. Wave steepness is defined as the ratio of the wave height divided by the wavelength. Wave height is defined as the vertical distance from a wave trough to the following wave crest. The wavelength is the horizontal distance between repeated features on the waveform such as crests, troughs or upward passes through the mean level.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'sea_surface_wave_maximum_steepness'}

name: Mean wave height
description: The mean wave height is the mean trough to crest distance measured during the observation period Wave height is defined as the vertical distance from a wave trough to the following wave crest.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'sea_surface_wave_mean_height'}

name: Mean Wave Period
description: Mean wave period. Average wave period over approximately 20 minutes. A period is an interval of time, or the time-period of an oscillation. Wave period is the interval of time between repeated features on the waveform such as crests, troughs or upward passes through the mean level. Wave mean period is the mean period measured over the observation duration.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'sea_surface_wave_mean_period'}

name: Mean wave period from first frequency moment
description: Mean Wave Period from the first frequency moment of the spectrum. Mean wave period over approx. 20 minutes. The wave directional spectrum can be written as a five dimensional function S(t,x,y,f,theta) where t is time, x and y are horizontal coordinates (such as longitude and latitude), f is frequency and theta is direction. S has the standard name sea_surface_wave_directional_variance_spectral_density. S can be integrated over direction to give S1= integral(S dtheta) and this quantity has the standard name sea_surface_wave_variance_spectral_density. Frequency moments, M(n) of S1 can then be calculated as follows: M(n) = integral(S1 f^n df), where f^n is f to the power of n. The first wave period, T(m1) is calculated as the ratio M(0)/M(1).
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'sea_surface_wave_mean_period_from_variance_spectral_density_first_frequency_moment'}

name: Wave period
description: The wave directional spectrum can be written as a five dimensional function S(t,x,y,f,theta) where t is time, x and y are horizontal coordinates (such as longitude and latitude), f is frequency and theta is direction. S can be integrated over direction to give S1= integral(S dtheta). Frequency moments, M(n) of S1 can then be calculated as follows: M(n) = integral(S1 f^n df), where f^n is f to the power of n. The second wave period, T(m2) is calculated as the square root of the ratio M(0)/M(2).
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'sea_surface_wave_mean_period_from_variance_spectral_density_second_frequency_moment'}

name: Mean wave steepness
description: Mean wave steepness is the mean value measured during the observation period. Wave steepness is defined as the ratio of the wave height divided by the wavelength. Wave height is defined as the vertical distance from a wave trough to the following wave crest. The wavelength is the horizontal distance between repeated features on the waveform such as crests, troughs or upward passes through the mean level.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'sea_surface_wave_mean_steepness'}

name: Maximum Wave Period from the spectrum
description: Wave period of the spectral density maximum. A period is an interval of time, or the time-period of an oscillation. The sea_surface_wave_period_at_variance_spectral_density_maximum, sometimes called peak wave period, is the period of the most energetic waves in the total wave spectrum at a specific location.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'sea_surface_wave_period_at_variance_spectral_density_maximum'}

name: Secondary Maximum Wave period from the spectrum
description: Wave period of the spectral density secondary maximum. A period is an interval of time, or the time-period of an oscillation. The secondayr maximum wave period is the period of the second most energetic waves in the total wave spectrum at a specific location.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'sea_surface_wave_period_at_variance_spectral_density_second_maximum'}

name: Period of the highest wave
description: Wave period of the highest wave is the period determined from wave crests corresponding to the greatest vertical distance above mean level during the observation period. A period is an interval of time, or the time-period of an oscillation. Wave period is the interval of time between repeated features on the waveform such as crests, troughs or upward passes through the mean level.

name: Significant Wave Height
description:
Significant wave height is a statistic computed from wave measurements and corresponds to the average height of the highest one third of the waves, where the height is defined as the vertical distance from a wave trough to the following wave crest. 
The parameter can be measured either instrumentally, manually or be an estimate from the wave radar spectrum. See the metadata of the given data source for details.

name: Wave steepness of highest wave
description: Wave steepness of the highest wave measured during the observation period. Wave steepness is defined as the ratio of the wave height divided by the wavelength. Wave height is defined as the vertical distance from a wave trough to the following wave crest. The wavelength is the horizontal distance between repeated features on the waveform such as crests, troughs or upward passes through the mean level.

name: Standard deviation of the wave steepness of the individual waves

The wavelength is the horizontal distance between repeated features on the waveform such as crests, troughs or upward passes through the mean level.

name: Wind wave direction

The direction is a bearing in the usual geographical sense, measured positive clockwise from due north.

name: Mean wave period, wind waves
description: Wave mean period of the wind waves. Wind waves are waves on the ocean surface and are the high frequency portion of a bimodal wave frequency spectrum. A period is an interval of time, or the time-period of an oscillation. Wave period is the interval of time between repeated features on the waveform such as crests, troughs or upward passes through the mean level. Wave mean period is the mean period measured over the observation duration.

name: Wave period of wind waves
description: The wind wave directional spectrum can be written as a five dimensional function S(t,x,y,f,theta) where t is time, x and y are horizontal coordinates (such as longitude and latitude), f is frequency and theta is direction. S can be integrated over direction, thus S1= integral(S dtheta). Frequency moments, M(n) of S1 can then be calculated as follows: M(n) = integral(S1 f^n df), where f^n is f to the power of n. The second wave period, T(m2), is calculated as the square root of the ratio M(0)/M(2).

description: Annual normal for precipitation sum calculated for the normal period 1961-1990.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'precipitation_amount_normal', 'method': 'sum', 'period': 'P1Y', 'addition': '1961_1990', 'methodDescription': 'The arithmetic sum of data values or accumulated value in a given period.'}

name: Normal for precipitation 1991-2020 (year)
description: Annual normal for precipitation sum calculated for the normal period 1991-2020.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'precipitation_amount_normal', 'method': 'sum', 'period': 'P1Y', 'addition': '1991_2020', 'methodDescription': 'The arithmetic sum of data values or accumulated value in a given period.'}

name: Evaporation (24 h)
description: Evaporated water from open water surface per 24 h
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'water_evaporation_amount', 'method': 'sum', 'period': 'P1D', 'methodDescription': 'The arithmetic sum of data values or accumulated value in a given period.'}

name: Evaporation (month)
description: Evaporated water from open water surface per month
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'water_evaporation_amount', 'method': 'sum', 'period': 'P1M', 'methodDescription': 'The arithmetic sum of data values or accumulated value in a given period.'}

name: Evaporation (season)
description: Evaporated water from open water surface per season. A season covers three months: Winter (Dec,Jan,Feb), spring (Mar,Apr,May), summer (Jun,Jul,Aug) and autumn (Sep,Oct,Nov).
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'water_evaporation_amount', 'method': 'sum', 'period': 'P3M', 'methodDescription': 'The arithmetic sum of data values or accumulated value in a given period.'}

name: Evaporation (1 h)
description: Evaporated water from open water surface per hour
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'water_evaporation_amount', 'method': 'sum', 'period': 'PT1H', 'methodDescription': 'The arithmetic sum of data values or accumulated value in a given period.'}

name: Accumulated precipitation, undefined period
description: Precipitation from station with occasional (non-daily) observations. Amount for period since last measurement.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'precipitation_amount', 'method': 'sum_over_undefined_period', 'methodDescription': 'Accumulated value since last observation, over undefined time periods greater than or equal (gte) the given time period. E.g. precipitation amounts from observations at irregular intervals.'}

name: Precipitation sum until day of year
description: Precipitation accumulated from 1 day of year until a certain day of year.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'precipitation_amount', 'method': 'sum_until_day_of_year', 'period': 'P1D', 'methodDescription': 'The arithmetic sum of datavalues in the period since 1. January to a day in the year.'}

name: Air pressure at station level
description: Air pressure at the station. The parameter is usually called QFE in aviation and shows the measured air pressure reduced to the reference height of the station.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'surface_air_pressure'}

name: Snow depth
description: The depth of the snow is measured in cm from the ground to the top of the snow cover. (Code=-1 means "no snow" and can be presented as ".")
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'surface_snow_thickness'}

name: Surface temperature
description: Surface temperature - snow surface or bare ground
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'surface_temperature'}

name: Sea Ice condition and trend
description: Present ice situation and trend of conditions over the preceding 3 hours. WMO code 5239, manual observation
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'tendency_of_sea_ice_condition'}

name: Air pressure characteristic (3 h)
description: Characteristic of the pressure tendency over the last three hours given by code 0-8, indicating whether pressure is rising, falling or steady.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'tendency_of_surface_air_pressure_type'}

name: Time of observation
description: The time an observation is made. This time is at the end of the inteval if the observation is valid for a timeinterval.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'time_of_observation'}

name: Time of observation interval beginning
description: The timestamp of the beginning of an irregular observational interval
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'time_of_observation_interval_start'}

name: Icing index
description: Icing index. Time since deicing on wessel.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'time_since_deicing_index'}

name: Unidirectivity index
description: The unidirectivity index indicates the percentage of total energy contained in the primary wave system. A directional wave spectrum parameter defined by Barstow et al (1991) indicating the directional homogeneity of the wave field; UI=1 if all mean wave directions are aligned.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'unidirectivity_index'}

name: Octant
description: Octant of the globe where the vessel is located. Used in SHIP-messages up until 1995.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'vessel_location_octant'}

name: Quadrant
description: Quadrant of the globe where the vessel is located. Used in SHIP-messages from 1996.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'vessel_location_quadrant'}

name: MOR visibility 1 min
description: MOR visibility in meters, now value.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'visibility_in_air_mor'}

name: Horisontal visibility in the operationally most significant direction
description: Horisontal visibility in the operationally most significant direction, from weather observations with aviation purposes (METAR). 0-5000 (in closest 100m), 5000-9998 (in closest 1000m), 9999 visibility > 10000 meter
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'visibility_in_air_operationally_significant'}

name: Visibility
description: Visibility. Converted from synop code (max 75 km) or metar code (max 10 km).
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'visibility_in_air_poorest_direction'}

name: Predominant or lowest horisontal visibility
description: Predominant or lowest horisontal visibility, from weather observations with aviation purposes (METAR). 0-5000 (in closest 100m), 5000-9998 (in closest 1000m), 9999 visibility > 10000 meter
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'visibility_in_air_predominant'}

name: Runway Visual Range
description: The horizontal distance down a runway a pilot of an aircraft can expect to see the runway surface markings or High Intensity Runway Lights. Automatically measured
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'visibility_in_air_rvr'}

name: Runway Visual Range tendency at runway id 1
description: The tendency of the Runway Visual Range at runway X1R. measured automatically. The runwayid can be found in the elementid runway_id1.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'visibility_in_air_rvr_tendency_x1r'}

name: Runway Visual Range tendency at runway id 2
description: The tendency of the Runway Visual Range at runway X2R. measured automatically. The runwayid can be found in the elementid runway_id2.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'visibility_in_air_rvr_tendency_x2r'}

name: Runway Visual Range tendency at runway id 3
description: The tendency of the Runway Visual Range at runway X3R. measured automatically. The runwayid can be found in the elementid runway_id3
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'visibility_in_air_rvr_tendency_x3r'}

name: Runway Visual Range excceeding measuring range at runwayid 1
description: One letter code that indicates if the Runway Visual Range exceeding measuring range, at runway id 1. The lower limit of the reporting range should be 50 m; below this limit, reports should merely indicate that the RVR is less than 50 m (M0050, code will be M). The upper limit of the reporting range should be 2000 m; above this limit, reports should merely indicate that the RVR is more than 2000 m (P2000, the code will be P). The runwayid can be found in the elementid runway_id1.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'visibility_in_air_rvr_validation_x1r'}

name: Runway Visual Range excceeding measuring range at runwayid 2
description: One letter code that indicates if the Runway Visual Range exceeding measuring range, at runway id 2. The lower limit of the reporting range should be 50 m; below this limit, reports should merely indicate that the RVR is less than 50 m (M0050, code will be M). The upper limit of the reporting range should be 2000 m; above this limit, reports should merely indicate that the RVR is more than 2000 m (P2000, the code will be P). The runwayid can be found in the elementid runway_id2.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'visibility_in_air_rvr_validation_x2r'}

name: Runway Visual Range excceeding measuring range at runwayid 3
description: One letter code that indicates if the Runway Visual Range exceeding measuring range, at runway id 3. The lower limit of the reporting range should be 50 m; below this limit, reports should merely indicate that the RVR is less than 50 m (M0050, code will be M). The upper limit of the reporting range should be 2000 m; above this limit, reports should merely indicate that the RVR is more than 2000 m (P2000, the code will be P). The runwayid can be found in the elementid runway_id3
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'visibility_in_air_rvr_validation_x3r'}

name: Runway Visual Range at runway id 1
description: The horizontal distance down a runway a pilot of an aircraft can expect to see the runway surface markings or High Intensity Runway Lights. Automatically measured at rundway id 1.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'visibility_in_air_rvr_x1r'}

name: Runway Visual Range at runway id 2
description: The horizontal distance down a runway a pilot of an aircraft can expect to see the runway surface markings or High Intensity Runway Lights. Automatically measured at rundway id 2.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'visibility_in_air_rvr_x2r'}

name: Runway Visual Range at runway id 3
description: The horizontal distance down a runway a pilot of an aircraft can expect to see the runway surface markings or High Intensity Runway Lights. Automatically measured at rundway id 3
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'visibility_in_air_rvr_x3'}

name: Visibility
description: Vertical visibility in meters, now value 10 minutes, calculated (with algoritm)
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'visibility_in_air_vertical_direction'}

name: Soil moisture
description: Soil moisture content at different depths (default 10 cm)
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'volume_fraction_of_water_in_soil'}

name: Present weather 1
description: Weather at time of observation, code (number or letter) for different types of weather, up to three codes may be given (Present weather 1-3). All three codes should be extracted when used.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'weather_class1_primary_significance'}

name: Present weather 2
description: Weather at time of observation, code (number or letter) for different types of weather, up to three codes may be given (Present weather 1-3). All three codes should be extracted when used.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'weather_class1_secondary_significance'}

name: Present weather 3
description: Weather at time of observation, code (number or letter) for different types of weather, up to three codes may be given (Present weather 1-3). All three codes should be extracted when used.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'weather_class1_tertiary_significance'}

name: Present weather
description: Weather at observation time, given as synoptic code 00-99
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'weather_type'}

name: Present weather, automatic
description: Weather at observation time, automatic measurement, given as synoptic code 00-99
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'weather_type_automatic'}

name: Prominent weather (METAR)
description: Prominent Significant Present Weather and Obscurations. Combinations of: Intensity: Light (-), Moderate (no prefix), Heavy (+). Descriptor (2 char. codes) / Precipitation  (2 char. codes). / Obscuration  (2 char. codes)
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'weather_type_primary_significance_metar'}

name: Second prominent weather (METAR)
description: Second Prominent Significant Present Weather and Obscurations. Combinations of: Intensity: Light (-), Moderate (no prefix), Heavy (+). Descriptor (2 char. codes) / Precipitation  (2 char. codes). / Obscuration  (2 char. codes)
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'weather_type_secondary_significance_metar'}

name: Third prominent weather (METAR)
description: Third Prominent Significant Present Weather and Obscurations. Combinations of: Intensity: Light (-), Moderate (no prefix), Heavy (+). Descriptor (2 char. codes) / Precipitation  (2 char. codes). / Obscuration  (2 char. codes)
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'weather_type_tertiary_significance_metar'}

name: Wind direction
description: Mean wind direction over the last ten minutes before the observation time. Wind direction is defined as the direction from which the wind blows and is registered in degrees, where 360 degrees is north and 90 degrees is east.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'wind_from_direction'}

name: Wind direction of wind gust
description: Wind direction at strongest gust
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'wind_from_direction_of_gust'}

name: Time when max wind speed has been measured (code) or an assessment of the wind conditions.
description: Code for when the maximum wind speed has been measured, or if the wind was increasing, decreasing or unchanged. National code used in older variants of the SYNOP-message.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'wind_info_synop'}

name: Wind shear at runway id
description: Wind shear at runway identification
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'wind_shear_at_runway_id'}

name: Wind shear at second runway id
description: Wind shear at second runway identification
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'wind_shear_at_second_runway_id'}

name: Mean wind speed
description: Mean wind speed is registered as a mean value of the wind speed over the last ten minutes before the observation time. (default: 10 meters above ground, some stations have measurements at 2 meters)
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'wind_speed'}

name: Wind gust
description: Highest wind gust since last observation. A wind gust is registered as a three second mean of the wind speed.
calculationMethod: {'baseName': 'wind_speed_of_gust'}
